Author: phm87#7395
Content: Verge (XVG) was forked to Shield (XSH), XSH team is competent, they helped XVG a while ago. XVG have lots of problems (slow wallet, weird consensus rules, memory leaks), I don't think that it is a good coin to fork. Other multi-algos coins exist and have a proper coinbase (DGB, Myriad). If you like to have more PoW algos, GLT have many many algos (unsure it is useful though)

Author: phm87#7395
Content: Launch a KMD assetchain is easier and cost less. If you fork a coin, you'll need to align your code to the changes of the parent coin (maintenance). With KMD assetchains, maintenance requires way less work than update yourself the code

Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[dscrd-hush] <Draeth (PhysicalCryptoCoins.com)> @halo kitty rules i've looked into a ton of different ways to include some sort of address (private or public). The downside to implementing a private address (whether it be via NFC, engraving, etc) is that most of the options would expose your private key to a third party, which to me, raises security concerns that I personally don't like and/or will make the coin look really tacky (specifically with implementing NFC).

As far as public addresses via engraving the address or QR code, i'm not opposed to it, but I do see some pitfalls. One of which, is if for some reason your address gets compromised, now you have a useless address/QR code on a coin. The other, being price. To get a unique QR code printed on every coin would drive up the price significantly (unless I can find someone to do the laser engraving for cheaper) and would also require that everyone who purchases a coin do the same (which, if I get enough interest and pre-orders for a coin specifically with this purpose, i'm all for it)
